2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n387,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Opportunity cost\"\" is the value of the next best alternative that is foregone when making a decision. It represents the cost of forgoing the next best option in favor of the chosen course of action. For instance, in the context of Division M, the opportunity cost is the lost contribution of $80 per unit when selling internally instead of externally. Similarly, for Push, the opportunity cost is the foregone sales proceeds of $3,000 when using a telephone system for a contract instead of selling it. Opportunity cost can also refer to the potential revenue from selling unused materials or the scrap value of materials not regularly used. It is a measure of the value of the benefit sacrificed when one course of action is chosen over another, highlighting the importance of considering the potential benefits of rejected alternatives. Lack of scarcity implies zero opportunity cost, as there would be no foregone alternatives.\",8\n390,\"\"\"RELEVANT COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Relevant cost refers to the cost that will be affected by a decision. It is the cost that will change as a result of choosing one alternative over another. Relevant costs are future costs that will differ between alternatives.\"\"\",7\n739,\"\"\"RELEVANT COST PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Relevant cost pricing\"\" involves setting prices based on the costs that will be incurred if a specific order is fulfilled, focusing on future incremental costs. This pricing strategy is often used for one-off projects, special orders, and tenders for contracts. It involves using existing resources and a relevant costing approach, where the price is calculated as the sum of relevant costs plus a mark-up. Additionally, relevant cost pricing, also known as opportunity cost pricing, is employed to set a minimum acceptable price to discourage new entrants and meet specific strategic goals. This approach is typically a short-term strategy aimed at pricing individual contracts or orders effectively.\",4\n391,\"\"\"MATERIALS FOR ONE-OFF CONTRACT\"\"\",\"\"\"Guidance for determining the relevant cost of materials for a one-off contract includes considering whether the materials have already been acquired and whether they are used regularly in the business. If not acquired, the current market price is the relevant cost. If acquired and used regularly, the replacement cost is the relevant cost. If not used regularly, the opportunity cost, such as scrap value, is the relevant cost.\"\"\",5\n1639,\"\"\"RELEVANT COSTING PRINCIPLES\"\"\",\"\"\"Relevant costs are those costs that change as a result of making a particular decision. They must meet three criteria: they must be future costs, involve cash flow, and be a direct consequence of the decision.\"\"\",4\n740,\"\"\"QUIZ: OPPORTUNITY COST PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the price Bobco Engineering should bid for a one-off contract, ensuring the costing is competitive and commercially rational. It includes various cost components such as standard steel, specialty steel, unskilled labor, semi-skilled labor, skilled labor, use of equipment, and exclusive use of a piece of manufacturing equipment.\"\"\",2\n2073,\"\"\"RELEVANT COST ANALYSIS FOR SPECIAL ORDER AT PARSER CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Parser Co is considering a one-off contract and needs to determine the relevant costs for pricing the special order. The analysis includes direct wages, supervisor costs, general overheads, machine depreciation, machine overheads, and materials, along with opportunity costs.\"\"\",2\n2074,\"\"\"RELEVANT COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Relevant costing involves identifying and considering only the costs that will be affected by a specific decision, including opportunity costs, to make informed financial decisions.\"\"\",2\n1390,\"\"\"SUNK COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Sunk costs are costs that have already been incurred and cannot be recovered. They are not relevant to future decision-making. For example, the $1.20 per metre for the cable is a sunk cost.\"\"\",6\n388,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"A company has been invited to tender for a contract to produce a component, R2D2. Production of R2D2 will require 100 hours of processing on Machine X. If Machine X is currently working at full capacity producing 50 units of Product Z an hour, each unit of Product Z makes a contribution of $2. If 100 hours of Machine X time is used to fulfill the new contract, the lost contribution of $10,000 (50 * $2 * 100) is an opportunity cost of producing R2D2 and should be taken into account when deciding how much to tender for the contract.\"\"\",1\n389,\"\"\"MINIMUM PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"The minimum price that makes a contract worthwhile is equal to the relevant cost. At this price, no profit or loss would be made on the contract.\"\"\",1\n398,\"\"\"ALTERNATIVE USES\"\"\",\"\"\"Alternative uses refer to other potential applications or purposes for materials or resources. In relevant cost analysis, considering alternative uses helps determine the opportunity cost of using materials for a specific project.\"\"\",1\n396,\"\"\"CURRENT MARKET PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Current market price is the price at which an asset or material can be bought or sold in the market at the present time. It is used as the relevant cost for materials that have not yet been acquired for a one-off contract.\"\"\",1\n392,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF RAW MATERIALS\"\"\",\"\"\"Crocus Co is considering making a new product that requires several types of raw material. The example details the relevant costs for materials A, B, and C based on their current purchase prices, inventory levels, and alternative uses.\"\"\",3\n397,\"\"\"INVENTORY LEVELS\"\"\",\"\"\"Inventory levels refer to the quantity of materials or products that a business has on hand. When determining relevant costs, inventory levels help assess whether existing materials can be used or if new materials need to be purchased.\"\"\",1\n393,\"\"\"QUIZ: RELEVANT COSTS OF MATERIALS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves determining the relevant costs for materials required by Bob, a carpenter, to make a special dining room table. The materials include oak wood, varnish, and hinges, each with different considerations for relevant cost calculation.\"\"\",3\n394,\"\"\"REPLACEMENT COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Replacement cost refers to the cost to replace an asset or material at its current market price. It is often used as the relevant cost when materials are regularly used in the business and need to be replenished.\"\"\",1\n395,\"\"\"SCRAP VALUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Scrap value is the estimated residual value of an asset or material at the end of its useful life. It is considered as the relevant cost when materials are not used regularly and could be sold off instead of being used in a new project.\"\"\",1\n400,\"\"\"BOB THE CARPENTER\"\"\",\"\"\"Bob is a carpenter featured in a quiz scenario where he needs to determine the relevant costs of materials (oak wood, varnish, and hinges) to make a special dining room table. Each material has different considerations for relevant cost calculation.\"\"\",2\n1389,\"\"\"COMPONENTS TO BUY IN\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves determining the cost-effectiveness of buying in components versus producing them in-house, considering material, labor, and variable overhead costs.\"\"\",1\n399,\"\"\"CROCUS CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Crocus Co is a hypothetical company used in an example to illustrate the relevant costs of raw materials for a new product. The example considers the current purchase prices, inventory levels, and alternative uses of materials A, B, and C.\"\"\",2\n1739,\"\"\"PRICING STRATEGIES\"\"\",\"\"\"Pricing strategies are methods used by companies to set the prices of their products. Examples include market skimming, market penetration, relevant cost pricing, and price discrimination by product version.\"\"\",2\n1385,\"\"\"RELEVANT CASH FLOW\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves identifying the best description of the term 'relevant cash flow,' which refers to the difference in future operating cash flows resulting from a decision.\"\"\",1\n1388,\"\"\"RELEVANT COST OF MATERIAL B FOR SPECIAL ORDER\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the total relevant cost of material B for a special order, considering the cost of quantity to be bought and the opportunity cost of quantity in hand.\"\"\",1\n1386,\"\"\"RELEVANT COST OF MATERIALS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the total relevant cost of materials for a project, considering the current purchase price and resale price of materials in inventory.\"\"\",1\n1387,\"\"\"SHORT-TERM DECISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves determining the truth of statements about short-term decisions, specifically regarding joint costs and differential costs between internal and external services.\"\"\",1\n1640,\"\"\"MINIMUM PRICE CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"MINIMUM PRICE CALCULATION\"\" is the process of determining the lowest price at which a company can sell a product without incurring a loss. This calculation includes relevant costs and may also consider opportunity costs and overheads. For instance, the minimum price per unit that Skulpt Co could set for LOK Co's order of the GSA is $60. This price is calculated by considering only the relevant costs: $30 for production, $24 for selling and distribution, and $6 for additional production costs.\",2\n1638,\"\"\"MODIFICATION COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Modification cost refers to the expenses incurred to alter or adapt an existing asset to meet specific requirements. In this context, the modification cost of $4,600 is the expense required to convert Swipe 1.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n361,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"TRANSFER PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Opportunity cost is a component of the transfer price calculation for Division M.\"\"\",21\n358,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"RELEVANT COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Opportunity cost is a type of Relevant cost that considers the value of the next best alternative foregone.\"\"\",15\n349,\"\"\"RELEVANT COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"RELEVANT COST PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Relevant Cost Pricing uses Relevant Costs to determine the minimum price for one-off projects, special orders, and tenders for contracts.\"\"\",14\n364,\"\"\"RELEVANT COST\"\"\",\"\"\"MATERIALS FOR ONE-OFF CONTRACT\"\"\",\"\"\"Relevant cost is a key concept in determining the Materials for one-off contract.\"\"\"\"Materials for one-off contract involves the concept of Relevant cost.\"\"\",12\n360,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"RELEVANT COSTING PRINCIPLES\"\"\",\"\"\"Opportunity cost is a key component of Relevant costing principles as it represents the value of the best alternative foregone due to a decision.\"\"\",12\n359,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: OPPORTUNITY COST PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on Opportunity Cost Price involves calculating the opportunity cost of various resources used in a one-off contract.\"\"\",10\n362,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST\"\"\",\"\"\"RELEVANT COST ANALYSIS FOR SPECIAL ORDER AT PARSER CO\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Relevant Cost Analysis for Special Order at Parser Co involves the concept of opportunity cost to determine the relevant costs for the special order.\"\"\",10\n363,